name: ROC Portfolio
tweet: 14/ That's enough to make me queasy about $ANET being my largest position.   So, I prefer View 1. I still own $ANET: it's about ~5% of the portfolio. FWIW, I think the company is poised to generate low single digit returns from here. Let's see if I'm pleasantly surprised.

name: ROC Portfolio
tweet: 13/ With $ANET, it isn't a clear-cut decision. And the fact that I'm conflicted tells me something: I don't understand this company as much as I should.   Yes I understand the business and the industry, but I don't know it enough to make a well-informed view on the future.

name: ROC Portfolio
tweet: 9/ At a price below $200 [where I bought], you were being more than compensated for these risks. You could buy $ANET for a mid-teens multiple and be fairly certain the business would continue to grow in the low double digits for ~5 years.

name: ROC Portfolio
tweet: 8/ I think looking 5 years out, white box becomes a pretty big issue. Either $ANET becomes a leading software player w/ EOS or they become a commoditized business with low returns. In either scenario, $ANET's revenues are hurt.

name: ROC Portfolio
tweet: 6/ The biggest existential threat facing $ANET is that it generates most of its revenues through hardware sales. As $CSCO painfully taught us, quickly commoditizing hardware is not the best place to operate in.

name: ROC Portfolio
tweet: 5/ I sold about half of my $ANET stake. Now, I have two conflicting views about this decision... Will go into both below.   View 1: I've learned things about the business that makes me less excited / price is getting ahead of itself.
